    type='think',
    think='Let me now read some more critical files to check for issues:\n1. The
BLoC tests\n2. The widgetbook main.dart\n3. The OpenAPI contract (docs/api-contr
acts/im.yaml)\n4. The conversation list cubit\n5. The im controller\n6. Check if
there are any design assets in designs/issue-5/\n\nI also need to look at:\n- Do
es the PR include `message:delivered` event in docs but the PRD mentions message
status should progress from "sending" to "sent" to "delivered"? Looking at the b
ackend gateway, it does emit `message:delivered` when receiver is online.\n- The
API docs say `message:ack` returns `{client_message_id, sequence_id}` but the ga
teway also returns `id`. The docs/api/im.md doesn\'t mention `id` in the ack.\n-
The `docs/api/socket-events.md` might have more details.\n\nLet me also check if
there are existing design assets and whether the PR followed the design-only PR 
requirement.\n\nLooking at the PR description, it says "实现 IM V1 即时通讯模块"
. It includes design system changes directly in the PR, not as a separate Design
-Only PR. According to the Flutter spec:\n"任何涉及新页面、新核心交互模式、新组
件的功能开发，必须严格遵守以下前置流程... Design-Only PR 先走"\n\nBut this is a 
feature PR, and the spec does say for `feat` tasks: `docs/exec-plans/TEMPLATE-fu
llstack-feature.md` is the first step. Let me check if there was an execution pl
an.\n\nActually, the PR is large and implements the full IM module. The design s
ystem changes are part of it. Let me check if there are designs from issue-5.\n\
nAlso, I noticed a potential issue in `im_bloc.dart`:\n- `_onReceiveMessage` ret
urns early without emitting state when message is for non-current conversation. 
It caches in `_pendingMessages`, but what if the state is `ImInitial`? Then when
the user opens that conversation, `LoadMessages` will merge pending. That seems 
okay.\n- But `_pendingMessages` has no cache limit! This could grow unbounded if
the user is in many conversations receiving many messages.\n\nAnother issue in `
ChatPage`:\n- `_getCurrentUserId()` is called inside `_buildChatItems` which is 
called in `build()`. It reads `context.read<AuthBloc>().state` during build, whi
ch is generally okay but could be inefficient. Not a blocking issue.\n\nIn `im.s
ervice.ts` `getConversations`:\n- The `nextCursor` is based on `updated_at` of t
he last conversation, but the query uses `updated_at < :cursor` with `new Date(c
ursor)`. If cursors have microsecond precision issues, this could be flaky. Not 
blocking.\n\nIn `im.gateway.ts`:\n- `handleConnection` catches errors with `catc
h { ... }` - if JWT verification fails, it disconnects. Good.\n- But there\'s no
`try/catch` around the `handleConnection` logic itself beyond the outer catch.\n
\nWait, I see a potential issue in `im.gateway.ts` handleConnection:\n```typescr
ipt\nconst payload = this.jwtService.verify(token);\n```\nIf the token is expire
d, this throws and the catch block disconnects. That\'s fine.\n\nBut wait - look
ing at the imports:\n```typescript\nimport { JwtService } from "@nestjs/jwt";\n`
``\nThis is `@nestjs/jwt` which was added as a dependency. But looking at `apps/
api/package.json` diff, `@nestjs/jwt` was added. Let me check the existing auth 
setup.\n\nLet me continue reading more files.',
    encrypted=None
)
