    type='think',
    think='Now let me check a few more things:\n\n1. The `MessageDto` in OpenAPI
has `status` enum: `[sent, read]`. But the backend also uses `delivered` and `se
nding` (client-side) and `failed` (client-side). The `sent` and `read` are serve
r-side statuses. Actually, looking at the database, `status` default is `"sent"`
. The server only stores `sent` or potentially `read`. Wait, `delivered` is a tr
ansient state emitted via socket but not persisted. `failed` and `sending` are c
lient-only. So the OpenAPI enum `[sent, read]` might be too restrictive if the s
erver doesn\'t actually store `read` in the DB. Let me check the DB entity - it 
has `default: "sent"` and no enum constraint. The OpenAPI says `enum: [sent, rea
d]` - this might be fine if read status is derived from `last_read_message_id`.\
n\nActually, looking at the PRD: "message status should progress from \'sending\
' to \'sent\' to \'delivered\'". But the DB only stores `sent`. The `delivered` 
status is tracked via socket events, and `read` is derived from `last_read_messa
ge_id`. So the OpenAPI `enum: [sent, read]` might be slightly misleading since t
he server doesn\'t actually update messages to `read` in the DB - it uses partic
ipant\'s `last_read_message_id`. But this is a minor API doc issue.\n\n2. I noti
ced `im.service.ts` `markAsRead` updates `last_read_message_id` but does NOT upd
ate message statuses in the DB to `read`. This is consistent with the PRD techni
cal requirement which says to update `conversation_participants.last_read_messag
e_id`. So messages table keeps `status = \'sent\'`, and read status is computed 
from `last_read_message_id`. This is correct.\n\n3. Let me check if there\'s an 
issue with `ImBloc` state emission. In `_onMessageAckReceived`, it emits `Messag
eSent` then immediately `MessagesLoaded`. The `MessageSent` state is only used f
or the listener to scroll to bottom. But looking at `ChatPage`:\n```dart\nlisten
er: (context, state) {\n  if (state is MessageSent) {\n    _scrollToBottom();\n 
}\n  if (state is MessagesLoaded && state.isInitialLoad) {\n    _scrollToBottom(
);\n    // ...\n  }\n}\n```\nThis is fine.\n\n4. Let me check if there\'s an iss
ue with `_onSendMessage` - when socket is connected, it emits `MessageSending` b
ut does NOT emit `MessagesLoaded` after. The message stays in `MessageSending` s
tate until ack arrives. But what if ack never arrives? The UI would be stuck in 
`MessageSending` state. Looking at `ChatPage` builder:\n```dart\nif (state is Me
ssagesLoaded || state is MessageSending || state is MessageSent) {\n  final mess
ages = state is MessagesLoaded ? ... : state is MessageSending ? ... : (state as
MessageSent).messages;\n```\nSo `MessageSending` is handled in the builder. But 
if the socket disconnects after `MessageSending` is emitted, there\'s no state t
ransition to `MessagesLoaded` with `isConnected: false`. This could be an issue 
- a message sent while connected but then socket drops before ack would remain i
n `sending` state forever (until maybe a reconnect and ack).\n\nWait, looking at
`_onImDisconnectRequested`:\n```dart\nif (state is MessagesLoaded) {\n  final cu
rrentState = state as MessagesLoaded;\n  emit(MessagesLoaded(\n    messages: cur
rentState.messages,\n    hasMore: currentState.hasMore,\n    nextCursor: current
State.nextCursor,\n    isConnected: false,\n    ...\n  ));\n}\n```\nIt only tran
sitions `MessagesLoaded` to `isConnected: false`. If the state is `MessageSendin
g` when disconnect happens, it stays `MessageSending`. This is a bug!\n\nBut is 
it blocking? The user can still see the message in `MessageSending` state, and t
he retry mechanism (`onRetry`) only shows for `failed` messages. So if the socke
t drops and never acks, the message is stuck in `sending` with no way to retry. 
This is a Major issue.\n\nActually, looking more carefully - when `_socketClient
?.isConnected` is true and `sendMessage` is called, the message is emitted as `M
essageSending`. If the socket then disconnects, the bloc state remains `MessageS
ending`. The user would see a sending spinner indefinitely.\n\nThis is a Major i
ssue.\n\n5. Another issue: In `_onSendMessage`, when socket IS connected, it emi
ts `MessageSending` but doesn\'t set `isConnected` to true in any following stat
e. The `ChatPage` displays the message list for `MessageSending` state but doesn
\'t have access to `hasMore`, `nextCursor`, etc. from the previous `MessagesLoad
ed` state. Let me check:\n\n```dart\nemit(MessageSending(\n    messages: newMess
ages, clientMessageId: clientMessageId));\n```\n\nThen in `ChatPage`:\n```dart\n
if (state is MessagesLoaded || state is MessageSending || state is MessageSent) 
{\n  final messages = state is MessagesLoaded\n      ? state.messages\n      : s
tate is MessageSending\n          ? state.messages\n          : (state as Messag
eSent).messages;\n\n  final chatItems = _buildChatItems(messages);\n\n  return S
wChatMessageList(\n    messages: chatItems,\n    isLoadingMore:\n        state i
s MessagesLoaded ? state.isLoadingMore : false,\n    onLoadMore: () {\n      fin
al nextCursor =\n          state is MessagesLoaded ? state.nextCursor : null;\n 
    if (nextCursor != null) {\n        context.read<ImBloc>().add(LoadMessages(.
..));\n      }\n    },\n    scrollController: _scrollController,\n  );\n}\n```\n
\nDuring `MessageSending`, `isLoadingMore` is false, and `onLoadMore` uses `next
Cursor: null` (since state is not `MessagesLoaded`). So pagination is disabled d
uring message sending. That\'s probably okay for a brief moment, but if the user
scrolls up to load more during the sending state, it won\'t work. This is a Mino
r UX issue.\n\n6. Looking at `im_bloc.dart` `_onReceiveMessage`:\n```dart\nif (e
vent.message.conversationId != _currentConversationId) {\n  _pendingMessages\n  
   .putIfAbsent(event.message.conversationId, () => [])\n      .add(event.messag
