an error, the BLoC doesn\'t know.\n\nI think this is Major.\n\nAnother potential
issue: In `im.service.ts` `getConversations`, the `lastMessages` raw query:\n```
typescript\nconst lastMessages = await this.dataSource.query(\n  `\n  SELECT m.*
FROM messages m\n  INNER JOIN (\n    SELECT conversation_id, MAX(sequence_id) as
max_seq\n    FROM messages\n    WHERE conversation_id IN (?)\n    GROUP BY conve
rsation_id\n  ) latest ON m.conversation_id = latest.conversation_id AND m.seque
nce_id = latest.max_seq\n`,\n  [conversationIds],\n);\n```\n\nIn MySQL/TypeORM, 
`IN (?)` with an array parameter might not expand correctly. This is a known iss
ue with some TypeORM versions. If `conversationIds` has more than one element, t
his could produce `IN (\'id1,id2\')` instead of `IN (\'id1\',\'id2\')`. This wou
ld break the last message query for users with multiple conversations.\n\nWait, 
TypeORM\'s `query()` method does handle array expansion for `?` placeholders in 
some cases. But looking at TypeORM source, for MySQL, arrays passed to `query()`
are typically serialized as comma-separated strings for `?` placeholders, but th
e driver might or might not expand them in `IN` clauses.\n\nActually, this is a 
known issue. In TypeORM, using `IN (:...ids)` in QueryBuilder works, but in raw 
`query()`, `?` with arrays is driver-dependent. For MySQL with mysql2 driver, ar
rays are typically expanded. But I\'m not 100% sure.\n\nGiven that this is the `
getConversations` core API and it could silently return wrong last messages for 
multi-conversation users, this is a significant risk. Let me classify this as Ma
jor.\n\nActually, looking at the test mock, it doesn\'t validate this. And in pr
oduction, if the SQL fails, it would throw an error. But if it incorrectly seria
lizes the array, it might just return fewer results or no results without throwi
ng. This is a data integrity issue for the conversation list.\n\nLet me check if
TypeORM with MySQL expands arrays in `query()`. From my knowledge, TypeORM\'s `q
uery()` method uses the underlying driver\'s parameter binding. For `mysql2`, wh
en you pass an array to `execute()` or `query()`, it does expand arrays for `?` 
